Is `suppress_compilation` just the same as tagging `noncomputable`?

Anyways, I'm wondering if it's possible to extract a version of `œâ` that very close to being a univariate polynomial, i.e. `Œ©` for `œâ` analogous to `Œ®` for `œà`, where `Œ©` is some univariate polynomial times a constant (2?) multiple of `œà`. This way the `ZSmul` formula can be expressed in affine coordinates as `n ‚Ä¢ (x, y) = (f(x), g(x) * h(x, y))` for some univariate rational functions `f` and `g` and some bivariate polynomial `h`, mirroring [Sutherland's statement in Lemma 5.21](https://math.mit.edu/classes/18.783/2023/LectureNotes5.pdf). When `a‚ÇÅ` and `a‚ÇÉ` are zero, then there should be a way to define `Œ©` so that `h(x, y)` is just `y`.

I'll see what I can do with œâ.

Lean is sometimes slow to compile something computable or fails to compile due to incomplete support. Verifying computability seems to always be fast though, so there should never be a need to mark a computable def `noncomputable`. To deal with slow compilation people have invented `suppress_compilation` and that's what we should use instead.

I'm not yet sure what could be done for `œâ`; the best idea I have is to take the expression
$$\omega_n=\frac{\psi_{n+1}\psi_n\psi_{n-1}}{\psi_3}(a_1 F_Y-F_X)-\frac{\psi_{n-2}\psi_{n+1}^2}{\psi_2}+(Y-F_Y)\psi_n^3$$
(first posted [on Zulip](https://leanprover.zulipchat.com/#narrow/stream/116395-maths/topic/Defining.20n-division.20polynomials/near/440352882), here I removed the multiple of `polynomial`) and try to analyze the even n and odd n cases separately. You can always write it as `p(X)+Yq(X)` in a unique way and maybe you will be able to compute the degrees of `p(X)` and `q(X)`.

An inadvertent discovery: when I tried to derive `negDblY` from $$\omega_2$$, I arrived at the very simple expression `œà‚ÇÉ polynomialX + Y polynomialY^3`. Comparing this with what we have in mathlib we arrive at the identity `œà‚ÇÉ + polynomialX^2 - a1 polynomialX polynomialY - (3x + a2) polynomialY^2 + (12 x + b2) polynomial = 0`. In my notes I've explained that `dblX` can be taken to be `X polynomialY^2 - œàh‚ÇÉ` where `œàh‚ÇÉ` is the weighted homogenization of `œà‚ÇÉ`. This new discovery shows that `negDblY` can be taken to be `Y polynomialY^3 + œàh‚ÇÉ polynomialX` which is of a similar form. TODO: use this to simplify the expressions [here](https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/pull/9417#discussion_r1769532231).

Thanks for the identities. I guess we'd have to either redefine `œàh‚ÇÉ` recursively, or get the homogenisation API working and apply it to the existing `œà‚ÇÉ`. It's probably not too urgent now but we should do it eventually.

The reason I'm asking for `Œ©` is because I need [Sutherland's argument for Theorem 5.8](https://math.mit.edu/classes/18.783/2023/LectureNotes5.pdf) to finish the computation for `|E[n]| = n^2`. We can translate that theorem into division polynomial language, and he essentially relates `|E[n]|` to the number of roots of `œà¬≤` (as a univariate polynomial), by showing that the fibers `(x‚ÇÄ, y‚ÇÄ)` of multiplication by `n` (after shifting `0` to a suitable point `(a, b)`) are uniquely determined by `x‚ÇÄ`, and we can show this easily if we have an expression for `œâ` directly in terms of `y`. The same argument happens to also work to show that multiplication by `n` is surjective (the "standard" proof to this is a non-trivial fact about morphisms of curves).

I don't think there's a need to define the whole family `œàh` recursively (which I think is what you mean); in any case `œàh‚ÇÉ` will be one of the base cases, so it either needs to be directly written down, or obtained from `œà‚ÇÉ` via homogenization API.
I'll read Sutherland to understand what is really needed.
